05835nam a22008415i 9780231550499DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019025151  a97802315504997 a10.7312/zeli193762doi  a(DE-B1597)545467  a(OCoLC)1108801776  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBP182 7aPOL0370002bisacsh04a297.72096112231 aZelin, Aaron Y., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYour Sons Are at Your Service :bTunisia's Missionaries of Jihad /cAaron Y. Zelin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Terrorism and Irregular Warfare00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tNOTE ON TRANSLITERATION -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. The Generation of Zaytunah -- t2. A Scattered Group with a Less- Than- Perfect Image -- t3. Come do Jihad -- t4. Sons of Tunisia -- t5. Tunisia is a Land of Dawa -- t6. Hear from Us, Not About Us -- t7. Tunisians Can Be Found Everywhere in the Land of Jihad -- t8. It Was Mostly the Tunisians Who Where Involved in Takfir -- t9. Honest Ones Among the Dawa People Must Come to al-Sham -- t10. We Are Here to Protect You from This Nonbeliever Government -- t11. The Future of the Tunisians Jihadi Movement -- tAuthor's Note on Terminology -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTunisia became one of the largest sources of foreign fighters for the Islamic State—even though the country stands out as a democratic bright spot of the Arab uprisings and despite the fact that it had very little history of terrorist violence within its borders prior to 2011. In Your Sons Are at Your Service, Aaron Y. Zelin uncovers the longer history of Tunisian involvement in the jihadi movement and offers an in-depth examination of the reasons why so many Tunisians became drawn to jihadism following the 2011 revolution.Zelin highlights the longer-term causes that affected jihadi recruitment in Tunisia, including the prior history of Tunisians joining jihadi organizations and playing key roles in far-flung parts of the world over the past four decades. He contends that the jihadi group Ansar al-Sharia in Tunisia was able to take advantage of the universal prisoner amnesty, increased openness, and the lack of governmental policy toward it after the revolution. In turn, this provided space for greater recruitment and subsequent mobilization to fight abroad once the Tunisian government cracked down on the group in 2013. Zelin marshals cutting-edge empirical findings, extensive primary source research, and on-the-ground fieldwork, including a variety of documents in Arabic going as far back as the 1980s and interviews with Ansar al-Sharia members and Tunisian fighters returning from Syria. The first book on the history of the Tunisian jihadi movement, Your Sons Are at Your Service is a meticulously researched account that challenges simplified views of jihadism’s appeal and success.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aIslam and politicszTunisia. 0aIslamic fundamentalismzTunisia. 0aJihad. 0aTerrorismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aTerrorist organizationszTunisia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311070281108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2020z978311069004008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eB